    "body": "I have an alternate proposal. The `20Gb` of preimage contains 50% preimages and 50% postmages. The postimages are fully derive:able from the preimages, so if we nuke those we've cut down `50%`. \r\nIf we also nuke the index, and dump it all out into a memory mapped file, we can probably shave down from `20Gb` to `8Gb` or less. \r\n\r\nSo then we'd wind up with a binary dump of preimages. Doing a binary search means `O(n log(n))` `sha3` operations/disk access, and so would an insert. We basically never ever search, so that's fine, and we could do inserts on some append-only file and compact it once every blue moon (e.g. at startup or shutdown)\r\n\r\nAnyway, it's non-core data, that wouldn't have to live in leveldb.",
